## .NET MAUI Shell Navigation with `IQueryAttributable`

### 1. Register the route

```csharp
// AppShell.xaml.cs
Routing.RegisterRoute("productdetails", typeof(ProductDetailsPage));
```

### 2. Navigate — two approaches

**A) String parameter (product ID):**
```csharp
// ProductListPage.xaml.cs or its ViewModel
await Shell.Current.GoToAsync($"productdetails?id={product.Id}");
```

**B) Full object via dictionary:**
```csharp
var navParams = new Dictionary<string, object>
{
    { "product", selectedProduct }   // passes the object reference directly
};
await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("productdetails", navParams);
```

### 3. Receive data — ViewModel implements `IQueryAttributable`

```csharp
public class ProductDetailsViewModel : ObservableObject, IQueryAttributable
{
    [ObservableProperty] string productId;
    [ObservableProperty] Product product;

    public void ApplyQueryAttributes(IDictionary<string, object> query)
    {
        // Approach A — simple string parameter
        if (query.TryGetValue("id", out var id))
            ProductId = id.ToString();

        // Approach B — full object
        if (query.TryGetValue("product", out var obj) && obj is Product p)
            Product = p;
    }
}
```

### 4. Wire the ViewModel to the page

```csharp
public partial class ProductDetailsPage : ContentPage
{
    public ProductDetailsPage(ProductDetailsViewModel vm)
    {
        InitializeComponent();
        BindingContext = vm;
    }
}
```

> Register both in `MauiProgram.cs`:
> ```csharp
> builder.Services.AddTransient<ProductDetailsPage>();
> builder.Services.AddTransient<ProductDetailsViewModel>();
> ```

### Key differences

| | String param | Object param |
|---|---|---|
| **Syntax** | `$"route?key={val}"` | `GoToAsync(route, dict)` |
| **Received as** | `string` (boxed in `object`) | Original object reference |
| **Deep-link safe** | ✅ Yes — survives URI serialization | ❌ No — in-memory only |
| **Use when** | Simple IDs, filters | You already have the object loaded |

Both approaches arrive in the same `ApplyQueryAttributes` call, so you can support both simultaneously as shown above.
